article.headline: California 78, Kansas State 48
article.story: BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Leon Powe's early departure to the NBA sure seems to have benefited California. Every player on the Golden Bears knows he must now do more -- and that's exactly what's happening. Ayinde Ubaka had 14 points, eight assists, three steals and no turnovers, DeVon Hardin added 12 points and 12 rebounds, and Cal beat cold-shooting Kansas State for the first time in six overall meetings with a 78-48 victory Wednesday night. "I think every win sends a message," Hardin said. "We're not a team that's going to come in and lay down. ... Everybody's been saying since Leon has left that we're not going to be a great rebounding team. I just go after it." Ryan Anderson had 15 points and seven rebounds in Cal's fifth straight win. The Bears (6-1) looked strong on both ends of the floor coming off their championship in the Great Alaska Shootout last weekend. This began a tough week for the team, which will face 24th-ranked Nevada on Sunday in the Pete Newell Challenge. "I liked our defensive intensity and our aggressiveness," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "Both of those went hand in hand. "Our team gained a lot of confidence in the Great Alaska Shootout." Cartier Martin scored 16 points and Lance Harris 14 for the Wildcats (4-2), who made their first trip to California since 1998 and first to Berkeley since 1958, only to be dealt the program's worst defeat in nearly three years. "I just didn't like our effort," K-State coach Bob Huggins said. "We knew they were good coming in. You look at their stats at halftime: Their center has 10 rebounds. That's what centers are supposed to do. Their point guard had seven assists. That's what you're supposed to do. Their shooter didn't miss a shot. That's what shooters are supposed to do." In that 1958 game, No. 3 KSU handed Cal its first loss on Dec. 12 and the Bears went on to win the '59 NCAA title at the end of that season under Hall of Fame coach Pete Newell. Wednesday's game marked the sixth meeting ever between the schools and first since 1995 -- the first four all were in the '50s. The game also was the first matchup between Huggins and Braun. The Bears won their 11th straight non-conference home game and held the Wildcats to a season low in points. "This is just another confidence builder," said Ubaka, who noted that Newell has been on him regularly about improving his defense. "We're setting a tone defensively. That's what Coach Braun preaches every day. That's what wins championships." Kansas State freshman 7-foot-3 center Jason Bennett matched a school record with six blocks and has three or more blocks in four of his six games. The Wildcats had won 22 of their last 27 non-conference games. They began the second half with a 5-0 spurt, then Cal went on an 11-2 run. The Wildcats' frustration came out when forward Luis Colon was ejected with 6:39 remaining for throwing a punch at Cal's Taylor Harrison. "He'll probably have to sit a game," Braun said. "Taylor can get under your skin. He plays hard." Kansas State started the game 9-for-26 while Cal made 13 of its first 24 shots and held the Wildcats without a point over the final 4:34 of the first half on the way to a 37-23 lead at the break. The Bears were whistled for only two first-half fouls to six for Kansas State. Hardin grabbed 10 of his boards in the first half. "DeVon really made a statement in the first half," Braun said. "That is the greatest contribution he can make. If he doesn't get those rebounds in the first half, I think it's a different game." A nearly 7-foot, 1,200-pound bronze statue of Newell was unveiled last month in the Club Room at Haas Pavilion -- and the 91-year-old Newell saw it for the first time Wednesday. "I think it's fine," said the modest Newell, who is in town from Southern California for his four-team event Sunday in San Jose. "What do you say about something like that? I'm tremendously grateful and honored. At a school like Berkeley, you don't see a lot of those around." Newell sat courtside below the basket and was introduced during a second-half timeout. The student section began chants of "We love Newell! We love Newell!"
